urg]] Metochion Serbian Orthodox Monastery, [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]. Nun Katherine, Superior.<ref>https://orthodox-world.org/en/i/25770/United-States/Indiana/Indianapolis/Monastery/St.-Xenia-Metochion-(St.-Xenia-Monastic-Community)</ref>\n*[[St. Pachomious Monastery]] [[Greenfield, Missouri]].\n\n== Georgian Orthodox Church ==\n===Female===\n* Sacred Monastery of St. Nina, [[Union Bridge, Maryland]]<ref>https://www.saintnina-monastery.org/</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External sources==\n\n{{OrthodoxWiki|name=List of American monasteries|oldid=51265}}\n* [http://www.goarch.org/en/archdiocese/monasteries/ Greek Orthodox Archdiocese Monastic Communities]\n\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox monasteries in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:United States religion-related lists|Eastern Orthodox Monasteries]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodoxy-related lists|Monasteries, United States]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Archimandtire->Archimandrite -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Eastern_Orthodox_monasteries_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Currie", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n | official_name=       Currie\n | country=             Scotland\n\n| static_image = Flag of Currie.svg\n| static_image_width = 200px\n| static_image_name = \n| static_image_caption = The Flag of Currie\n| static_image_2 = Coat of Arms of Currie.svg\n| static_image_2_width = 150px\n| static_image_2_name = Coat of Arms\n| static_image_2_caption = The Coat of Arms of Currie\n\n | area_total_sq_mi=     \n | area_total_km2=       \n| population = 7,494\n| population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011]])\n  | os_grid_reference=   NT182677 \n | map_type=            Scotland\n | coordinates = {{coord|55.895956|-3.307439|display=inline,title}}\n | post_town=           CURRIE\n | postcode_area=       EH\n | postcode_district=   EH14\n | dial_code=           0131\n | constituency_westminster=    [[Edinburgh South West (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh South West]] \n | constituency_scottish_parliament=  [[Edinburgh Pentlands (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh Pentlands]] \n | london_distance=     \n | gaelic_name=         Currach\n | scots_name=          Curry\n | unitary_scotland=    [[City of Edinburgh]]\n}}\n\n'''Currie''' ({{lang-gd|Currach}}) is a [[suburb]] of [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]], situated {{convert|7|mi|km|0|abbr=off}} south west of the city centre. A former village within the County of [[Midlothian]], it lies to the south west of the city, between [[Juniper Green]] (NE) and [[Balerno]] (SW) on the [[A70 road|Lanark Road]]. Administratively, Currie falls within the jurisdiction of the [[Politics of Edinburgh|City of Edinburgh Council]]. It gives its name to a [[Civil parishes in Scotland|civil parish]].\n\nIn 2001 the population of Currie was 8,550 and it contained 3,454 houses.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.currie-scc.gov.uk/ccc11.html | title = Currie Community Council | accessdate = 2012-06-24}}</ref>\n \n== Etymology ==\nThere is no accepted derivation of the name Currie but it is possibly from the [[Scottish Gaelic]] word ''curagh/curragh'', a wet or boggy plain, or from the [[British language (Celtic)|Brythonic]] word ''curi'', a dell or dirt hole.  The neighbouring suburb of [[Balerno]] derives its name from [[Scottish Gaelic]], whilst the nearby [[Pentland Hills]] derive their name from Brythonic, so either is possible.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe earliest record of a settlement in the Currie area is a [[Bronze Age]] razor (1800 BC) found at Kinleith Mill and the stone cists (500 BC) at Duncan's Belt and Blinkbonny. There are a few mentions of this area in [[mediaeval]] and early modern documents. One of the first is when Robert of Kildeleith became Chancellor of Scotland in 1249. Kildeleith means Chapel by the Leith, and survives today as Kinleith. [[Robert the Bruce]] gave [[Riccarton, Edinburgh|Riccarton]] as a wedding present in 1315 and in 1392 the land passed to the family of Bishop Wardlaw. In 1612 the land went to Ludovic Craig, a Senator of the [[College of Justice]]. In 1818 it passed to the female line and became the property of the Gibson-Craigs.\n\nThere has been a Christian community in the area for more than 1,000 years. In 1018, the archdeacons of [[Lothian]] set up their headquarters in the area. [[John Bartholomew]]'s Civic and Ecclesiastical maps of the 13th century do not show Currie, but the Index of Charters 1309-1413 records Currie as being 'favourite hunting grounds' for the Lords and Knights of [[Edinburgh Castle]]. A settlement began to take shape around Currie Kirk and the main Lanark Road, which was the main route south and continues to be known as 'The [[Lang Whang]]'.\n\nThe weaver poet [[James Thomson (weaver poet)|James Thomson]] was brought up in the village in the late 18th century and is commemorated by the dell of the Kinleith Burn being named the \"Poet's Glen\", where it runs down from beside his cottage at Mid Kinleith Farm to join the Water of Leith, and also by a number of street names, (Thomson Road, Thomson Drive, Thomson Crescent), in the east of Currie.\n\nThe war memorial was erected in 1919 to a design by Sir [[Robert Lorimer]].<ref>Dictionary of Scottish Architects: Robert Lorimer</ref>\n\nThe period 1921-1951 brought great changes with the building of more council houses in Currie and private building along Lanark Road. Wider scale development began in the late 1950s and early 1960s with the construction of a private housing estate to the east of Curriehill Road. House builders began to promote Currie as a pleasant commuting suburb of Edinburgh and much house building took place to the north of Lanark Road West. Currie High School was constructed on its present site in 1966 and extensively refurbished and renewed in 1997. There was a [[Currie railway station|Currie station]] on [[Balerno line|a short loop railway]] running over what is now the [[Water of Leith Walkway]]. The physical topography has ensured that the original historic core to the south of Lanark Road West including the Water of Leith has remained undeveloped. In March 1972 the historic centre of Currie was declared a [[Conservation Area]].\n\n== Education ==\nThe earliest record of education in the area is contained in the Minutes of Edinburgh Town Council in 1598, when Baillie Lawrence Henderson was sent to \"the toun o Currie to help the gentlemen of the Parish select a Schoolmaister\"; however it is not stated where the school was situated. In 1694, the heritors appointed a Mr Thomson to teach scholars in the Church until Thomas Craig of Riccarton found a place for the building of a school and house for the schoolmaster. The foundations of the school were laid in 1699. The school and school house cost 500 merks and the salary of the schoolmaster was 20 pounds Scots per year.\n\nCurrie is served by [[Currie High School]] (which has been a Green Flag Eco-School since 2004), Nether Currie Primary School and Currie Primary School, formed by an amalgamation in 2005 of Curriehill Primary School and Riccarton Primary School which shared neighbouring campuses. The largest single Year group since the School's inception, was 1984. According to the School Website this number will probably never be equalled or exceeded. CHS has sought to improve facilities since 2000 with additions of All Weather, floodlit Football Pitches. \n\nFrom the 1970s onwards, [[Heriot-Watt University]] moved from its city centre location to occupy the lands of the former Riccarton Estate, gifted to the university by Midlothian County Council in 1966. The move has now been completed and the main campus of Heriot-Watt University occupies and manages a wooded area with enough space for future expansion.\n\n== Sport ==\n\n=== Football ===\nCurrie has two youth football teams Currie Football Club and Currie Star FC (Currie Star play their games in the [[Kingsknowe]] area of [[Edinburgh]]).\n\n=== Rugby ===\nCurrie has one rugby team, Currie RFC who are based and play their home games in the neighbouring village of [[Balerno]].\n\n== Culture and attractions ==\nCurrie has two Scout Groups - the 31st Pentland which has run continuously since 1924 and the 42nd Pentland.\n\nCurrie is a District of Girlguiding Edinburgh.  1st Currie Guides have run continuously since 1921, and 1st Currie Brownies continually since 1933.\n\nOn the first Saturday of May The Currie Riding of the Marches takes place.\n\n== Local History Society ==\n\nCurrie and District Local History Society meets 12 times a year and has speakers on all aspects of the area.\n\nThe society meets every first and third Monday in the month and their year starts in October.\nThe venue is in the Gibson Craig Hall on the Lanark Road in Currie.\n\n==Ethnicity==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Currie compared !! Currie !! Edinburgh\n|-\n| White || 92.6% || 91.7%\n|-\n| Asian || 3.8% || 5.5%\n|-\n| Black || 2.3% || 1.2%\n|-\n| Mixed || 0.5% || 0.9%\n|-\n| Other || 0.8% || 0.8%\n|}\n\n== Transport ==\n{{See also|Transport in Edinburgh}}\n\nThe [[A70 road|A70]] runs through the area and Currie is serviced by the [http://lothianbuses.com/plan-a-journey/timetables/44 44] and [http://lothianbuses.com/plan-a-journey/timetables/45 45] bus routes, which are operated by [[Lothian Buses]]. Currie is served by rail by [[Curriehill railway station]] on the [[Shotts Line|Glasgow-Edinburgh via Shotts Line]]. Currie is also close to the City of Edinburgh bypass and is bordered by the [[Union Canal (Scotland)|Union Canal]] to the north and the [[Water of Leith]] to the south. Edinburgh Airport is located approximately {{convert|4|mi|km|0|abbr=off}} north of Currie and the M8 motorway to [[Glasgow]] is around {{convert|2|mi|km|0|abbr=off}} north. It also has connections to Livingston in West Lothian through [http://www.horsburghcoaches.com E&M Horsburgh] service [https://web.archive.org/web/20141213024702/http://www.horsburghcoaches.com/timetable.php?id=96 24], between Juniper Green and Livingston.\n\n==Currie Kirk==\n\n[[File:Currie Kirk, Midlothian.JPG|thumb|275px|Currie Kirk and war memorial]]\nThe parish church lies south of the current main road, amongst a small cluster of buildings which represent the original village. It was built in a simple rectangular form, with a pediment on its north (entrance) side and a low central spire, in 1784 by James Thompson of [[Leith]]. Its interior was remodelled in 1835 by the [[Edinburgh]] architect, [[David Bryce]], and in 1848 the windows were enlarged by the architect [[David Cousin]]. As the graveyard pre-dates the church it is presumed that the church replaced an earlier church.<ref>Buildings of Scotland: Lothian  by Colin McWilliam</ref>\n\nThe graveyard is laid out in three sections: an original section around the church including several interesting carved stones from the 17th and 18th centuries; a Victorian section on a raised tier; and an attached, but separately walled cemetery to the south, containing 20th century graves.\n\nThe [[war memorial]]. which adopts the form of a medieval [[market cross]], stands near the entrance to the church. It was designed by Sir [[Robert Lorimer]] and added in 1921.<ref>Dictionary of Scottish Architects: Robert Lorimer</ref>\n\nBelow the site of the church close to the Water of Leith is St Mungo's Holy Well with its stone basin and side walls.\n\n===Ministers===\n*Rev James Craig in 1780s<ref>williamsons Street Directory 1784</ref>\n*Rev James Dick ministered 1792 to 1815<ref>Grave of Rev James Dick, Currie Kirkyard</ref>\n*Rev Dr James Langwill ministered 1859 to 1898<ref>Memorial to James Langwill in Currie Kirk</ref>\n\n===Notable Interments===\n*[[Alick Buchanan-Smith, Baron Balerno]] (1898-1984)\n*[[Alick Buchanan-Smith (1932\u20131991)|Alick Laidlaw Buchanan-Smith]] MP (1932-1991)\n*Sir [[Stanley Davidson]] (1894-1981) Professor of Medicine\n*William Henderson (1766-1842) co-founder of [[Scottish Widows]] (large obelisk to the north-west of the churchyard)\n*Dr [[Robert Cranston Low]] MD FRCPE [[FRSE]] (1879-1949) medical author\n*Dr [[Alexander Morison]] (1779-1866)\n*[[Ochterlony baronets|Sir David Ferguson Ochterlony]] (1848-1931) 3rd Baronet Ochterlony\n*Sir [[George Adam Smith]] (1856-1942) including a memorial to his daughter, [[Janet Adam Smith]]\n*Brigadier General Ernest Craig Brown, who gives his name to the military march \"Captain Craig Brown\"<ref>https://boxandfiddlearchive.weebly.com/captain-craig-brown.html</ref>\n\n== Famous residents ==\n\n* [[Stephen Carter, Baron Carter of Barnes]]\n* [[Jamie Dick]] - Youth Olympic Gold Medalist in Curling\n* [[Kate Green]] - Labour MP\n* [[Dougal Haston]] - pioneer of Scottish mountaineering\n* [[Matthew Lloyd]] - Australian Rules footballer, [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]]\n* [[Maitland Moir|John Henry Maitland Moir]] - Archimandrite, Greek Orthodox Church of St Andrew\n* [[Matt Scott (rugby union)|Matt Scott]] - Scottish international Rugby Union player\n* [[James Thomson (weaver poet)]]\n*Paul Research and John Mackie of post-punk band [[Scars (band)|The Scars]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edinburghgigarchive.com/page31.htm|title=The Edinburgh Gig Archive - Odds & Ends|website=www.edinburghgigarchive.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-07}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Heriot-Watt University]]\n*[[Currie High School]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20100329115029/http://www.curriechs.co.uk/ [last accessed 26 Feb 1013]\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110903142315/http://www.currie-scc.gov.uk/ Currie Community Council]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100329115029/http://www.curriechs.co.uk/ Currie Community High School]\n*[http://www.currierugby.org Currie Rugby Football Club]\n*[http://www.hw.ac.uk Heriot-Watt University]\n*[http://www.currie-pri.edin.sch.uk Currie Primary School]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100609065108/http://www.ltscotland.org.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/nethercurrieprimaryschooledinburghcity.asp Nether Currie Primary's page on Scottish Schools Online]\n*[http://www.curriehistory.org Currie and District Local history Society]\n*[http://www.nethercurrie.edin.sch.uk Nether Currie Primary School]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T4t4WGIDAJo St Mungo's Well]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AQ0tSJqr_QU Curriehill railway station]\n{{Areas of Edinburgh}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Parishes formerly in Midlothian]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n | official_name=       Currie\n | country=             Scotland\n\n| static_image = Flag of Currie.svg\n| static_image_width = 200px\n| static_image_name = \n| static_image_caption = The Flag of Currie\n| static_image_2 = Coat of Arms of Currie.svg\n| static_image_2_width = 150px\n| static_image_2_name = Coat of Arms\n| static_image_2_caption = The Coat of Arms of Currie\n\n | area_total_sq_mi=     \n | area_total_km2=       \n| population = 7,494\n| population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011]])\n  | os_grid_reference=   NT182677 \n | map_type=            Scotland\n | coordinates = {{coord|55.895956|-3.307439|display=inline,title}}\n | post_town=           CURRIE\n | postcode_area=       EH\n | postcode_district=   EH14\n | dial_code=           0131\n | constituency_westminster=    [[Edinburgh South West (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh South West]] \n | constituency_scottish_parliament=  [[Edinburgh Pentlands (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh Pentlands]] \n | london_distance=     \n | gaelic_name=         Currach\n | scots_name=          Curry\n | unitary_scotland=    [[City of Edinburgh]]\n}}\n\n'''Currie''' ({{lang-gd|Currach}}) is a [[suburb]] of [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]], situated {{convert|7|mi|km|0|abbr=off}} south west of the city centre. A former village within the County of [[Midlothian]], it lies to the south west of the city, between [[Juniper Green]] (NE) and [[Balerno]] (SW) on the [[A70 road|Lanark Road]]. Administratively, Currie falls within the jurisdiction of the [[Politics of Edinburgh|City of Edinburgh Council]]. It gives its name to a [[Civil parishes in Scotland|civil parish]].\n\nIn 2001 the population of Currie was 8,550 and it contained 3,454 houses.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.currie-scc.gov.uk/ccc11.html | title = Currie Community Council | accessdate = 2012-06-24}}</ref>\n \n== Etymology ==\nThere is no accepted derivation of the name Currie but it is possibly from the [[Scottish Gaelic]] word ''curagh/curragh'', a wet or boggy plain, or from the [[British language (Celtic)|Brythonic]] word ''curi'', a dell or dirt hole.  The neighbouring suburb of [[Balerno]] derives its name from [[Scottish Gaelic]], whilst the nearby [[Pentland Hills]] derive their name from Brythonic, so either is possible.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe earliest record of a settlement in the Currie area is a [[Bronze Age]] razor (1800 BC) found at Kinleith Mill and the stone cists (500 BC) at Duncan's Belt and Blinkbonny. There are a few mentions of this area in [[mediaeval]] and early modern documents. One of the first is when Robert of Kildeleith became Chancellor of Scotland in 1249. Kildeleith means Chapel by the Leith, and survives today as Kinleith. [[Robert the Bruce]] gave [[Riccarton, Edinburgh|Riccarton]] as a wedding present in 1315 and in 1392 the land passed to the family of Bishop Wardlaw. In 1612 the land went to Ludovic Craig, a Senator of the [[College of Justice]]. In 1818 it passed to the female line and became the property of the Gibson-Craigs.\n\nThere has been a Christian community in the area for more than 1,000 years. In 1018, the archdeacons of [[Lothian]] set up their headquarters in the area. [[John Bartholomew]]'s Civic and Ecclesiastical maps of the 13th century do not show Currie, but the Index of Charters 1309-1413 records Currie as being 'favourite hunting grounds' for the Lords and Knights of [[Edinburgh Castle]]. A settlement began to take shape around Currie Kirk and the main Lanark Road, which was the main route south and continues to be known as 'The [[Lang Whang]]'.\n\nThe weaver poet [[James Thomson (weaver poet)|James Thomson]] was brought up in the village in the late 18th century and is commemorated by the dell of the Kinleith Burn being named the \"Poet's Glen\", where it runs down from beside his cottage at Mid Kinleith Farm to join the Water of Leith, and also by a number of street names, (Thomson Road, Thomson Drive, Thomson Crescent), in the east of Currie.\n\nThe war memorial was erected in 1919 to a design by Sir [[Robert Lorimer]].<ref>Dictionary of Scottish Architects: Robert Lorimer</ref>\n\nThe period 1921-1951 brought great changes with the building of more council houses in Currie and private building along Lanark Road. Wider scale development began in the late 1950s and early 1960s with the construction of a private housing estate to the east of Curriehill Road. House builders began to promote Currie as a pleasant commuting suburb of Edinburgh and much house building took place to the north of Lanark Road West. Currie High School was constructed on its present site in 1966 and extensively refurbished and renewed in 1997. There was a [[Currie railway station|Currie station]] on [[Balerno line|a short loop railway]] running over what is now the [[Water of Leith Walkway]]. The physical topography has ensured that the original historic core to the south of Lanark Road West including the Water of Leith has remained undeveloped. In March 1972 the historic centre of Currie was declared a [[Conservation Area]].\n\n== Education ==\nThe earliest record of education in the area is contained in the Minutes of Edinburgh Town Council in 1598, when Baillie Lawrence Henderson was sent to \"the toun o Currie to help the gentlemen of the Parish select a Schoolmaister\"; however it is not stated where the school was situated. In 1694, the heritors appointed a Mr Thomson to teach scholars in the Church until Thomas Craig of Riccarton found a place for the building of a school and house for the schoolmaster. The foundations of the school were laid in 1699. The school and school house cost 500 merks and the salary of the schoolmaster was 20 pounds Scots per year.\n\nCurrie is served by [[Currie High School]] (which has been a Green Flag Eco-School since 2004), Nether Currie Primary School and Currie Primary School, formed by an amalgamation in 2005 of Curriehill Primary School and Riccarton Primary School which shared neighbouring campuses. The largest single Year group since the School's inception, was 1984. According to the School Website this number will probably never be equalled or exceeded. CHS has sought to improve facilities since 2000 with additions of All Weather, floodlit Football Pitches. \n\nFrom the 1970s onwards, [[Heriot-Watt University]] moved from its city centre location to occupy the lands of the former Riccarton Estate, gifted to the university by Midlothian County Council in 1966. The move has now been completed and the main campus of Heriot-Watt University occupies and manages a wooded area with enough space for future expansion.\n\n== Sport ==\n\n=== Football ===\nCurrie has two youth football teams Currie Football Club and Currie Star FC (Currie Star play their games in the [[Kingsknowe]] area of [[Edinburgh]]).\n\n=== Rugby ===\nCurrie has one rugby team, Currie RFC who are based and play their home games in the neighbouring village of [[Balerno]].\n\n== Culture and attractions ==\nCurrie has two Scout Groups - the 31st Pentland which has run continuously since 1924 and the 42nd Pentland.\n\nCurrie is a District of Girlguiding Edinburgh.  1st Currie Guides have run continuously since 1921, and 1st Currie Brownies continually since 1933.\n\nOn the first Saturday of May The Currie Riding of the Marches takes place.\n\n== Local History Society ==\n\nCurrie and District Local History Society meets 12 times a year and has speakers on all aspects of the area.\n\nThe society meets every first and third Monday in the month and their year starts in October.\nThe venue is in the Gibson Craig Hall on the Lanark Road in Currie.\n\n==Ethnicity==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Currie compared !! Currie !! Edinburgh\n|-\n| White || 92.6% || 91.7%\n|-\n| Asian || 3.8% || 5.5%\n|-\n| Black || 2.3% || 1.2%\n|-\n| Mixed || 0.5% || 0.9%\n|-\n| Other || 0.8% || 0.8%\n|}\n\n== Transport ==\n{{See also|Transport in Edinburgh}}\n\nThe [[A70 road|A70]] runs through the area and Currie is serviced by the [http://lothianbuses.com/plan-a-journey/timetables/44 44] and [http://lothianbuses.com/plan-a-journey/timetables/45 45] bus routes, which are operated by [[Lothian Buses]]. Currie is served by rail by [[Curriehill railway station]] on the [[Shotts Line|Glasgow-Edinburgh via Shotts Line]]. Currie is also close to the City of Edinburgh bypass and is bordered by the [[Union Canal (Scotland)|Union Canal]] to the north and the [[Water of Leith]] to the south. Edinburgh Airport is located approximately {{convert|4|mi|km|0|abbr=off}} north of Currie and the M8 motorway to [[Glasgow]] is around {{convert|2|mi|km|0|abbr=off}} north. It also has connections to Livingston in West Lothian through [http://www.horsburghcoaches.com E&M Horsburgh] service [https://web.archive.org/web/20141213024702/http://www.horsburghcoaches.com/timetable.php?id=96 24], between Juniper Green and Livingston.\n\n==Currie Kirk==\n\n[[File:Currie Kirk, Midlothian.JPG|thumb|275px|Currie Kirk and war memorial]]\nThe parish church lies south of the current main road, amongst a small cluster of buildings which represent the original village. It was built in a simple rectangular form, with a pediment on its north (entrance) side and a low central spire, in 1784 by James Thompson of [[Leith]]. Its interior was remodelled in 1835 by the [[Edinburgh]] architect, [[David Bryce]], and in 1848 the windows were enlarged by the architect [[David Cousin]]. As the graveyard pre-dates the church it is presumed that the church replaced an earlier church.<ref>Buildings of Scotland: Lothian  by Colin McWilliam</ref>\n\nThe graveyard is laid out in three sections: an original section around the church including several interesting carved stones from the 17th and 18th centuries; a Victorian section on a raised tier; and an attached, but separately walled cemetery to the south, containing 20th century graves.\n\nThe [[war memorial]]. which adopts the form of a medieval [[market cross]], stands near the entrance to the church. It was designed by Sir [[Robert Lorimer]] and added in 1921.<ref>Dictionary of Scottish Architects: Robert Lorimer</ref>\n\nBelow the site of the church close to the Water of Leith is St Mungo's Holy Well with its stone basin and side walls.\n\n===Ministers===\n*Rev James Craig in 1780s<ref>williamsons Street Directory 1784</ref>\n*Rev James Dick ministered 1792 to 1815<ref>Grave of Rev James Dick, Currie Kirkyard</ref>\n*Rev Dr James Langwill ministered 1859 to 1898<ref>Memorial to James Langwill in Currie Kirk</ref>\n\n===Notable Interments===\n*[[Alick Buchanan-Smith, Baron Balerno]] (1898-1984)\n*[[Alick Buchanan-Smith (1932\u20131991)|Alick Laidlaw Buchanan-Smith]] MP (1932-1991)\n*Sir [[Stanley Davidson]] (1894-1981) Professor of Medicine\n*William Henderson (1766-1842) co-founder of [[Scottish Widows]] (large obelisk to the north-west of the churchyard)\n*Dr [[Robert Cranston Low]] MD FRCPE [[FRSE]] (1879-1949) medical author\n*Dr [[Alexander Morison]] (1779-1866)\n*[[Ochterlony baronets|Sir David Ferguson Ochterlony]] (1848-1931) 3rd Baronet Ochterlony\n*Sir [[George Adam Smith]] (1856-1942) including a memorial to his daughter, [[Janet Adam Smith]]\n*Brigadier General Ernest Craig Brown, who gives his name to the military march \"Captain Craig Brown\"<ref>https://boxandfiddlearchive.weebly.com/captain-craig-brown.html</ref>\n\n== Famous residents ==\n\n* [[Stephen Carter, Baron Carter of Barnes]]\n* [[Jamie Dick]] - Youth Olympic Gold Medalist in Curling\n* [[Kate Green]] - Labour MP\n* [[Dougal Haston]] - pioneer of Scottish mountaineering\n* [[Matthew Lloyd]] - Australian Rules footballer, [[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]]\n* [[Maitland Moir|John Henry Maitland Moir]] - Archimndrite, Greek Orthodox Church of St Andrew\n* [[Matt Scott (rugby union)|Matt Scott]] - Scottish international Rugby Union player\n* [[James Thomson (weaver poet)]]\n*Paul Research and John Mackie of post-punk band [[Scars (band)|The Scars]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edinburghgigarchive.com/page31.htm|title=The Edinburgh Gig Archive - Odds & Ends|website=www.edinburghgigarchive.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-07}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Heriot-Watt University]]\n*[[Currie High School]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\nhttps://web.archive.org/web/20100329115029/http://www.curriechs.co.uk/ [last accessed 26 Feb 1013]\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110903142315/http://www.currie-scc.gov.uk/ Currie Community Council]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100329115029/http://www.curriechs.co.uk/ Currie Community High School]\n*[http://www.currierugby.org Currie Rugby Football Club]\n*[http://www.hw.ac.uk Heriot-Watt University]\n*[http://www.currie-pri.edin.sch.uk Currie Primary School]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100609065108/http://www.ltscotland.org.uk/scottishschoolsonline/schools/nethercurrieprimaryschooledinburghcity.asp Nether Currie Primary's page on Scottish Schools Online]\n*[http://www.curriehistory.org Currie and District Local history Society]\n*[http://www.nethercurrie.edin.sch.uk Nether Currie Primary School]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T4t4WGIDAJo St Mungo's Well]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AQ0tSJqr_QU Curriehill railway station]\n{{Areas of Edinburgh}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Parishes formerly in Midlothian]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Archimndrite->Archimandrite -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Currie"}
{"title_page": "Veronica bucket", "text_new": "{{Infobox product\n| title            = Veronica Bucket\n| image            = Veronica Bucket 5.jpg|\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Bucket]]\n| inventor         = [[Veronica Bekoe]]\n| inception        = \n| manufacturer     = \n| available        = Available\n| current supplier =\n| last production  = \n| models           = \n| website          = \n| notes            = \n}}\n\nA '''veronica''' '''bucket''' is sanitation set-up originating in [[Ghana]] with a bucket, a tap fixed at the bottom and held above a bowl serving as a simple way to encourage proper [[hand washing]].<ref name=\"graphic\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/lifestyle/life/ghana-news-why-is-this-bucket-called-veronica-bucket.html|title=Why is this bucket called 'veronica bucket'?|last=|first=|date=|website=Graphic.come.gh|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe bucket is also used in other [[Africa]]n countries. It is common in places such as schools, hospitals, churches and in areas with no running taps.<ref name=\"graphic\" /> It has become very popular in Ghana following the outbreak of the novel Corona virus ([[COVID-19]]) as citizens engage in frequent hand washing to stem its spread.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalcommunitiesgh.org/index.php/telling-our-story/62-saving-lives-with-a-little-soap-and-water-new-behavior-change-communication-package-promotes-healthy-hygiene-practices|title=Saving Lives with a Little Soap and Water: New Behavior Change Communication Package promotes healthy hygiene practices - Global Communities Ghana|website=www.globalcommunitiesgh.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/other/banks-in-suhum-step-up-measures-against-coronavirus-spread/ar-BB11ANUJ|title=Banks in Suhum step up measures against coronavirus spread|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> In [[Ekiti State]], [[Nigeria]], the governor [[Kayode Fayemi]] directed all public places to provide running tapwater or Veronica buckets \"to encourage frequent handwashing\" as part of the measures to contain COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ani |first1=Emmanual |title=COVID-19: Ekiti shuts down schools, institutions |url=https://dailypost.ng/2020/03/20/covid-19-ekiti-shuts-down-schools-institutions/ |website=Daily Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nBefore the Covid-19 outbreak, the invention was used in some schools and hospitals but is in high demand due to its role in curbing the outbreak. Now, the set up could\u00a0 be spotted in places like the malls, corporate institutions and government offices. It was invented by a Ghanaian, [[Veronica Bekoe]], whom the invention was named after. Bekoe was a biological scientist who worked at the Public Health and Reference Laboratory of the [[Ghana Health Service]] from 1972 to 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Veronica-Bucket-The-Ghanaian-invention-helping-in-coronavirus-fight-895813|title=Veronica Bucket: The Ghanaian invention helping in coronavirus fight|website=www.ghanaweb.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nThe invention was initially produced by local [[artisans]] with wood and has an area for holding soap and\u00a0 towels. Variations available today are made of [[plastic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/traders-cash-in-on-veronica-buckets-as-demand-goes-up-due-to-covid-19/|title=Traders cash in on Veronica buckets as demand goes up due to COVID-19|date=2020-03-25|website=Citinewsroom |language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n{{Commons|Category:Veronica_Bucket}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category: Health in Ghana]]\n[[Category: Medical technology]]\n\nhttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Veronica_Bucket\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox product\n| title            = Veronica Bucket\n| image            = Veronica Bucket 5.jpg|\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Bucket]]\n| inventor         = [[Veronica Bekoe]]\n| inception        = \n| manufacturer     = \n| available        = Available\n| current supplier =\n| last production  = \n| models           = \n| website          = \n| notes            = \n}}\n\nA '''veronica''' '''bucket''' is sanitation set-up originating in [[Ghana]] with a bucket, a tap fixed at the bottom and held above a bowl serving as a simple way to encourage proper [[hand washing]].<ref name=\"graphic\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/lifestyle/life/ghana-news-why-is-this-bucket-called-veronica-bucket.html|title=Why is this bucket called 'veronica bucket'?|last=|first=|date=|website=Graphic.come.gh|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe bucket is also used in other [[Africa]]n countries. It is common in places such as schools, hospitals, churches and in areas with no running taps.<ref name=\"graphic\" /> It has become very popular in Ghana following the outbreak of the novel Corona virus ([[COVID-19]]) as citizens engage in frequent hand washing to stem its spread.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalcommunitiesgh.org/index.php/telling-our-story/62-saving-lives-with-a-little-soap-and-water-new-behavior-change-communication-package-promotes-healthy-hygiene-practices|title=Saving Lives with a Little Soap and Water: New Behavior Change Communication Package promotes healthy hygiene practices - Global Communities Ghana|website=www.globalcommunitiesgh.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/other/banks-in-suhum-step-up-measures-against-coronavirus-spread/ar-BB11ANUJ|title=Banks in Suhum step up measures against coronavirus spread|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> In [[Ekiti State]], [[Nigeria]], the governor [[Kayode Fayemi]] directed all public places to provide running tapwater or Veronica buckets \"to encourage frequent handwashing\" as part of the measures to contain COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ani |first1=Emmanual |title=COVID-19: Ekiti shuts down schools, institutions |url=https://dailypost.ng/2020/03/20/covid-19-ekiti-shuts-down-schools-institutions/ |website=Daily Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nBefore the Covid-19 outbreak, the invention was used in some schools and hospitals but is in high demand due to its role in curbing the outbreak. Now, the set up could\u00a0 be spotted in places like the malls, corporate institutions and government offices. It was invented by a Ghanaian, [[Veronica Bekoe]], whom the invention was named after. Bekoe was a biological scientist who worked at the Public Health and Reference Laboratory of the [[Ghana Health Service]] from 1972 to 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Veronica-Bucket-The-Ghanaian-invention-helping-in-coronavirus-fight-895813|title=Veronica Bucket: The Ghanaian invention helping in coronavirus fight|website=www.ghanaweb.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nThe invention was initially produced by local [[artisans]] with wood and has an area for holding soap and\u00a0 towels. Variations available today are made of [[plastic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/traders-cash-in-on-veronica-buckets-as-demand-goes-up-due-to-covid-19/|title=Traders cash in on Veronica buckets as demand goes up due to COVID-19|date=2020-03-25|website=Citinewsroom |language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category: Health in Ghana]]\n[[Category: Medical technology]]\n", "name_user": "Jwale2", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Category Session", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veronica_bucket"}
{"title_page": "\u00c1lvarez (surname)", "text_new": "{{Infobox surname\n| name = \u00c1lvarez\n| image=\n| imagesize= \n| caption= \n| meaning =  Son of \u00c1lvaro; alternatively, from Arabic ''al-faris'', a knight or cavalryman<ref>https://www.genealogy.com/forum/surnames/topics/alvarez/228/</ref>\n| region = Spain\n| language = Spanish\n| variant = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''\u00c1lvarez''' (sometimes ''Alvarez'') is a Spanish surname.\n\nAmong those with the surname are:\n\n*[[Al Alvarez]], English writer\n*[[Ana \u00c1lvarez]], Spanish model and actress\n*[[Ana Albertina Delgado \u00c1lvarez]], Cuban artist\n* Onion News Network's Brooke Alvarez, played by [[Suzanne Sena]]\n*[[Carlos \u00c1lvarez (baritone)]], Spanish opera singer\n*[[Carlos \u00c1lvarez (mayor)]], U.S. politician\n*[[Celia \u00c1lvarez Mu\u00f1oz]] (born 1932), American artist\n*[[Ciriaco \u00c1lvarez]] (born 1873), [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago|Chilo\u00e9]] businessman\n*[[Emilio \u00c1lvarez Lejarza]], Nicaraguan jurist and political writer\n*[[Emilio \u00c1lvarez Montalv\u00e1n]], Nicaraguan ophthalmologist and political writer\n*[[Enrique \u00c1lvarez F\u00e9lix]], Mexican actor\n*[[Eugenio Alvarez]] (1918\u20131976), New York assemblyman\n*[[Everett Alvarez, Jr.]], U.S. military and war prisoner\n*[[Fede \u00c1lvarez]] (born 1978), Uruguyan filmmaker\n*[[Felix Alvarez]], Gibraltar human and civil rights activist and defender\n*[[Francisco \u00c1lvarez (actor)]], Argentine actor\n*[[Gregorio \u00c1lvarez (historian)]] (1889-1986), Argentine physician and historian\n*[[Gregorio Conrado \u00c1lvarez]], Uruguayan general and dictator\n*[[Javier \u00c1lvarez (composer)]], Mexican composer\n*[[Jos\u00e9 \u00c1lvarez Cubero]] (23 April 1768 - 26 November 1827), Spanish sculptor in the neoclassical style\n*[[Jos\u00e9 \u00c1lvarez de Toledo, Duke of Alba]], Spanish patron of painter Goya\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Manuel \u00c1lvarez]], Argentine politician\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda \u00c1lvarez de Sotomayor]], Spanish playwright and poet\n*Jos\u00e9 Sixto \u00c1lvarez, aka [[Fray Mocho]], Argentine writer\n*[[Juan \u00c1lvarez (historian)]], Argentine judge and historian\n*[[Juan \u00c1lvarez]], Mexican general and president\n*Juan Manuel Alvarez, man convicted of causing the [[2005 Glendale train crash]]\n*[[Julia Alvarez]], U.S. writer\n*[[Juli\u00e1n \u00c1lvarez (lawyer)|Juli\u00e1n \u00c1lvarez]], Argentine politician\n*[[Karl Alvarez]], U.S. musician\n*[[Luis F. \u00c1lvarez]], U.S. physician, father of Mabel Alvarez and Walter C. Alvarez\n*[[Luis Walter Alvarez]] (1911\u20131988), U.S. physicist, and recipient of the Nobel Prize in Physics, son of Walter C. Alvarez, father of Walter Alvarez\n*[[Lynn Alvarez]]\n*[[Mabel Alvarez]], U.S. oil painter, daughter of Luis F. \u00c1lvarez\n*[[Mariano \u00c1lvarez de Castro]], Spanish Brigadier\n*[[Mariano \u00c1lvarez]], Filipino general, statesman, and teacher\n*[[Melania Alvarez]], Mexican mathematics educator in Canada\n*[[Miguel \u00c1lvarez-Fern\u00e1ndez]], Spanish composer\n*[[Nancy Alvarez (psychologist)]], Dominican psychologist and TV presenter\n*[[Pedro \u00c1lvarez Castell\u00f3]], Cuban painter\n*[[Pedro de Toledo, 1st Marquis of Mancera]], Spanish viceroy of Peru\n*[[Pedro \u00c1lvarez de Toledo, Marquis of Villafranca]], Spanish viceroy of the Kingdom of Naples\n*[[Pero Alvarez]], 15th-century freed slave\n*[[Robert Alvarez]], U.S. animator, television director, and writer\n*[[Rosendo \u00c1lvarez Gast\u00f3n]] (1926\u20132014), Spanish Roman Catholic bishop\n*[[Roy Alvarez]] (1950\u20132014), Filipino actor, director and screenwriter\n*[[Severiano \u00c1lvarez]] (1933\u20132013), Spanish writer\n*[[Vincent Alvares]] (1680-1738), Indian doctor and clergyman\n*[[Walter Alvarez]], U.S. geologist responsible for discovering the reasons behind Cretaceous\u2013Tertiary extinction event, son of Luis Walter Alvarez\n*[[Walter C. Alvarez]], U.S. physician, son of Luis F. \u00c1lvarez, father of Luis Walter Alvarez\n*[[