entine rugby player\n*[[Robin \u00c1lvarez]], Swedish ice hockey player\n*[[Tony \u00c1lvarez]] (born 1979), Venezuelan baseball player\n*[[Veronica Alvarez]] (born 1983), American baseball catcher\n*[[Wilson \u00c1lvarez]], Venezuelan baseball player\n*[[Wilson Alvarez (American football)]] (born 1957), Bolivian player of American football\n*[[Yadier \u00c1lvarez]], baseball pitcher\n\n{{surname}}<!-- It does not help to add disambig or hndis tags where the page only contains people who share a surname -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alvarez (Surname)}}\n[[Category:Italian-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Patronymic surnames]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Archipealgo->Archipelago -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%81lvarez_(surname)"}
{"title_page": "Beatrice of Castile (1293\u20131359)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{other people|Beatrice of Castile}}\n{{Infobox royalty|consort=yes\n| name         = Beatrice of Castile\n| image = Beatrice of Castile (1293-1359).jpg\n| caption =\n| succession   = [[Queen consort of Portugal]]\n| reign        = 7 January 1325{{snd}}28 May 1357\n| spouse       = [[Afonso IV, King of Portugal]]\n| issue        =  [[Maria of Portugal, Queen of Castile|Maria, Queen of Castile]]<br>[[Peter I of Portugal]]<br> [[Eleanor of Portugal, Queen of Aragon|Eleanor, Queen of Aragon]]\n| issue-pipe   = Among others\u2026\n| issue-link   = #Issue\n| house        = [[Castilian House of Ivrea]]\n| father       = [[Sancho IV, King of Castile]]\n| mother       = [[Mar\u00eda de Molina]]\n| birth_date   = 8 March 1293\n| birth_place  =\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1359|10|25|1293|||df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Lisbon]], Portugal\n| burial_place = [[Lisbon Cathedral]]\n}}\n'''Beatrice of Castile''' or '''Beatriz''' (8 March 1293{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=350}}{{snd}}25 October 1359),{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=314}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} was an [[infanta]] of [[Crown of Castile|Castile]], daughter of [[Sancho IV of Castile|Sancho IV]] and [[Mar\u00eda de Molina]]. She was [[List of Portuguese consorts|Queen of Portugal]] from the accession of her husband, [[Afonso IV]],{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=305}} until his death on 28 May 1357.{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=311}}\n\n== Biography ==\n=== Family origins and early years ===\nDaughter of Sancho IV  and of Mar\u00eda de Molina,{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=312}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=215}} Infanta Beatrice was born in [[Toro, Zamora|Toro]]. She had six siblings, including King [[Ferdinand IV of Castile]] and  Queen [[Isabella of Castile, Queen of Aragon|Isabella]], wife of King  [[James II of Aragon]], and later duchess as the wife of [[John III, Duke of Brittany]].{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=215}}\n\nOn 13 September 1297, when Beatrice was only four years old, the bilateral agreement, known as the [[Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices]], was signed between Castile and Portugal, putting an end to the hostilities between both kingdoms and establishing the definitive borders. The treaty was signed by Queen Mar\u00eda de Molina, as the [[regent]] of Castile on behalf of her son, Ferdinand IV, who was still a minor, and King Denis of Portugal. To reinforce the peace, the agreement included clauses arranging the marriages of King Ferdinand and [[Constance of Portugal]] and that of her brother, Afonso, with Beatrice; that is, the marriage of two siblings, infantes of Portugal, with two other siblings, infantes of Castile.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=215}}{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|pp=350-351}}{{Sfn|Gonz\u00e1lez M\u00ednguez|2004|p=228\u2013229}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|The marriage of Ferdinand and Constance had been negotiated in a previous agreement signed on 15 September 1291. King Sancho IV of Castile  later negotiated the marriage of his son Ferdinand with Blanche, daughter of King [[Philip IV of France]].{{Sfn|Gonz\u00e1lez M\u00ednguez|2004|pp=225\u2013226}} The [[Engagement|betrothal]] of Ferdinand and Constance was ratified as part of the Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices in 1297.{{Sfn|Gonz\u00e1lez M\u00ednguez|2004|p=228}}}}\n\nBeatrice abandoned Castile in the same year and moved to the neighboring kingdom where she was raised in the court of King Denis together with her future spouse, Infante Afonso, who at that time was about six years old.{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=354}} Her future father-in-law \"had inherited from his grandfather, [[Alfonso X of Castile]], a love of letters, literature, Portuguese poetry, and the art of the [[troubadour]]s\" and Beatrice grew up in this refined environment.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=215-216}} Two of the Portuguese king's illegitimate sons, both important figures in the kingdom's cultural panorama, were also at the court: [[Pedro Afonso, Count of Barcelos]], a poet and troubadour and the author of ''Cr\u00f3nica Geral de Espanha'' and the ''Livro de Linhagens''; and, [[Afonso Sanches, Lord of Albuquerque|Afonso Sanches]], the favorite son of King Denis and a celebrated troubadour.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=216}}\n\n=== ''Arras'' and properties===\n[[File:Obidos 05.JPG|thumb|300px|[[\u00d3bidos, Portugal|\u00d3bidos castle]], given to Beatrice by her son Peter I of Portugal]]\nAfter the signing of the Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices and upon their return to Portugal, King Denis gave his future daughter-in-law the ''[[Las arras|Carta de Arras]]'' (wedding tokens) which included the ''[[Manorialism|se\u00f1or\u00edos]]'' of [[\u00c9vora]], [[Vila Vi\u00e7osa]], [[Vila Real, Portugal|Vila Real]] and [[Vila Nova de Gaia]] which generated an annual income of more than 6000 pounds of the old Portuguese currency.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=216}}{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=354}} After the marriage, these estates were increased. In 1321, her husband, who had not ascended to the throne yet, gave her [[Viana do Alentejo]]; in 1325, he gave her other properties in [[Santar\u00e9m, Portugal|Santar\u00e9m]]; in 1337, properties in Atalaia; in 1341, a manor house in [[Alenquer, Portugal|Alenquer]]; in 1350, the prior  of the Monastery of San Vicente de Fora gave her Melide, a manor house in [[Sintra]]; and later, in 1357, her son, King Peter, gave her more estates which included [[\u00d3bidos, Portugal|\u00d3bidos]], [[Atouguia, Our\u00e9m|Atouguia]], [[Torres Novas]], [[Our\u00e9m]], [[Porto de M\u00f3s]], and Chilheiros.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=227}}\n\n=== Marriage ===\nThe marriage was celebrated in Lisbon on 12 September 1309.{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=312}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} Before the marriage could take place, a [[papal dispensation]] was required since Afonso was a great-grandson of King Alfonso X of Castile through his illegitimate daughter, [[Beatrice of Castile (1242\u20131303)|Beatrice of Castile]], and Beatrice, betrothed to Afonso, was a granddaughter of the same Castilian king. In 1301, [[Pope Boniface VIII]] issued the [[papal bull]] authorizing the marriage, but since both were underage, it was postponed until 1309 when Afonso was eighteen years old and Beatrice had turned sixteen.{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=355}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=216-217}} It was a fertile and apparently happy marriage. Afonso broke the tradition of previous kings and did not have any children out of wedlock.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|\"We assume that after the marriage of dona Beatriz and don Alfonso IV, married life was harmonious (...) based on the fact that D. Afonso IV did not have any bastard children, thereby breaking a long family tradition\" (loose translation){{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=356}}}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|\"Perhaps since he had so many problems with those of his father, D. Afonso did not have any illegitimate children.\" (loose translation){{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|\"There are no known bastard children of the king. Two possible explanations could be the ties of profound esteem, friendship and respect that existed because he had been raised and had lived from a very early age with his future wife or, perhaps, because he wanted to avoid that his heirs had the same problems that he had had with his bastard brothers\".(loose translation){{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}}} Four out of the seven children born of this marriage died in their infancy.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=216-217}}\n\n=== A reconciling queen ===\nLike her mother-in-law, [[Elizabeth of Aragon]], who had raised her as a child, during her marriage Beatrice played a relevant role in the affairs of the kingdom and was \"the first foreign-born queen who was perfectly versed in the language and customs of Portugal which facilitated her role as a mediator of conflicts\".{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=225}} She discreetly supported her husband when he confronted his father on account of his half-brother, Afonso Sanches. In 1325 after the death of King Denis, Afonso \"who had not forgotten former hatreds\", demanded to be acclaimed king by the [[Curia regis|court]] and was responsible for having his half brother [[Jo\u00e3o Afonso, Lord of Lous\u00e3|Jo\u00e3o Afonso]] killed, and his great rival, his other bastard brother, Afonso Sanches, banished to Castile\".{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=222}}\n\nWhen her husband and her son-in-law King Alfonso XI of Castile fought in the war that took place in 1336{{snd}}1339, Beatrice crossed the border and went to [[Badajoz]] to meet the Castilian king to try to reach an agreement that would bring peace to both kingdoms, although her efforts proved to be fruitless.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=223}} She sent her ambassadors in 1338 to the court of King [[Alfonso IV of Aragon]] to strengthen the alliance between both kingdoms which had been weakened when her son, the future King Peter I of Portugal, refused to marry Blanche, a niece of the Aragonese king because of her proven \"mental weakness (...) and her incapacity for marriage\".{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=223}}\n\nQueen Beatrice and Guilherme de la Garde, [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Braga#List of Archbishops of Braga|Archbishop of Braga]], acted as mediators in the quarrel, which lasted almost one year and posed the threat of another civil war in the Kingdom of Portugal following the assassination of [[In\u00e9s de Castro]],{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=355}} and in 1355, father and son reached an agreement.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=223}}\n\nOn the religious front, she founded a hospital in 1329 in Lisbon and later, with her husband, the Hospital da S\u00e9 to treat twenty-four poor people of both sexes, providing the institution with all that was required for its day-to-day maintenance.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=226}} In her [[Will and testament|last wills]] and [[Codicil (will)|codicil]], she left many properties and sums for religious establishments, particularly for the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] and [[Franciscan]] orders, and asked to be buried wearing the simple robe of the latter order.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=236-237}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=314}}\n\n=== Issue ===\nBeatrice and Alfonso IV were the parents of the following infantes:\n\n* [[Maria of Portugal, Queen of Castile|Maria]] (1313{{snd}}18 January 1357),{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|pp=315, 317 and 322}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} was the wife of [[Alfonso XI of Castile]],{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} and mother of the future king [[Peter I of Castile]]. Due to the affair of her husband with his mistress [[Leonor de Guzm\u00e1n]] \"it was an unfortunate union from the start, contributing to dampening the relations of both kingdoms\";{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=218}} \n* Afonso ([[Penela]], 1315{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}{{snd}}1317), heir to the throne, died in his infancy.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} Buried at the disappeared Convento das Donas of the Dominican Order in Santar\u00e9m;{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}  \n* Denis (born 12 February 1317 in Santar\u00e9m),{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}} heir to the throne, died a few months after his birth,{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|He died sometime before 13 June 1317 as evidenced by a letter from [[Pope John XII]] to King Denis expressing his condolences for the death of his grandson.{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201, n.208}}}} and was buried in [[Alcoba\u00e7a Monastery]];{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}} \n* [[Peter I of Portugal|Peter]] (8 April 1320{{snd}}18 January 1367), the first surviving male offspring, he succeeded his father.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} {{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} When his wife [[Constance of Pe\u00f1afiel|Constance]] died in 1345, Queen Beatrice took care of the education of the two orphans, the infantes [[Maria, Marchioness of Tortosa|Maria]] and Ferdinand, who later reigned as King [[Ferdinand I of Portugal]];{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=228-229}}\n* Isabel (21 December 1324{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{snd}}11 July 1326{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}), buried at the [[Monastery of Santa Clara-a-Velha]] in [[Coimbra]];{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}  \n* John (23 September 1326{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}{{snd}}21 June 1327{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}), buried at the [[Monastery of S\u00e3o Dinis de Odivelas]];{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}\n* [[Eleanor of Portugal, Queen of Aragon|Eleanor]] (1328{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=359}}{{snd}}1348), born in the same year as her sister Maria's wedding,{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} she married King [[Peter IV of Aragon]] in November 1347 in Barcelona{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=362}} and died a year after her marriage succumbing to the Black Death.{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=363}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=217, 220}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}\n\n=== Death and burial===\n[[File:Cloisters of S\u00e9 de Lisboa - Jun 2009.jpg|thumb|Cloisters of Lisbon Cathedral where King Ferdinand IV and Beatrice of Castile were buried]]\nQueen Beatrice executed three wills and one codicil.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=232-233}} She died in Lisbon when she was 66 years old and was buried at [[Lisbon Cathedral]] next to her husband as she had stipulated in her will.{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=314}} While the definitive tombs were being built, the royal couple was originally buried at the choir of the church and it was not until the reign of King [[John I of Portugal|John I]] that their remains were transferred to the new sepulchers in the main chapel of the cathedral.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=234-235}} These sepulchers were destroyed during the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake]] and were replaced in the 18th century. The ''Livros do Cart\u00f3iro da S\u00e9'' (Charters of the Cathedral) written between 1710 and 1716, describe the burial of Queen Beatrice, very similar to that of her husband, with an engraving that read: ''Beatriz Portugaliae Regina / Affonsi Quarti Uxor''.(Beatrice Queen of Portugal, wife of Afonso IV).{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=238}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite news|last= Gonz\u00e1lez M\u00ednguez|first = C\u00e9sar|year = 2004|title = Fernando IV de Castilla (1295-1312): Perfil de un reinado|work = Espacio, Tiempo y Forma, Serie III, Historia Medieval|number= 17| pages=223\u2013244|publisher = Universidad Nacional de Educaci\u00f3n a Distancia (UNED), Facultad de Geograf\u00eda e Historia |location = Madrid| issn = 0214-9745| url  = http://e-spacio.uned.es/fez/eserv/bibliuned:ETFB795938A-A8EF-AC9F-1889-B989699FFC79/Documento.pdf|language=ES|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite news|last = Louren\u00e7o Menino|first = Vanda Lisa|year = 2008|title = Cartas de Arras da Rainha D. Beatriz (1309-1359)|work = Estudios human\u00edsticos. Historia|number = 7|pages = 349\u2013358|publisher = Universidad de Le\u00f3n: Servicio de Publicaciones|location = Le\u00f3n|language = PT|issn = 1696-0300|url = http://buleria.unileon.es/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10612/1167/EUH-7-12.pdf?sequence=1|ref = harv|access-date = 11 June 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140418233835/http://buleria.unileon.es/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10612/1167/EUH-7-12.pdf?sequence=1|archive-date = 18 April 2014|url-status = dead}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Rodrigues Oliveira|first= Ana|title= Rainhas medievais de Portugal. Dezassete mulheres, duas dinastias, quatro s\u00e9culos de Hist\u00f3ria|language= PT |publisher= A esfera dos livros |location = Lisbon| year= 2010|isbn= 978-989-626-261-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last = Sotto Mayor Pizarro|first = Jos\u00e9 Augusto|title = Linhagens Medievais Portuguesas: Genealogias e Estrat\u00e9gias (1279-1325|location =Oporto|publisher=Doctorate thesis, author\u2019s edition|year= 1997|language = PT |url=http://hdl.handle.net/10216/18023|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last =Sousa|first =Ant\u00f3nio Caetano de|title = Historia Geneal\u00f3gica da Casa Real Portugueza|location = Lisbon|year= 1735| publisher =Lisboa Occidental, of. de Joseph Antonio Da Sylva, Impressor da Academia Real|oclc=3910285|language = PT|url = http://purl.pt/776/4/hg-2593-v/hg-2593-v_item4/hg-2593-v_PDF/hg-2593-v_PDF_24-C-R0150/hg-2593-v_0000_1-800_t24-C-R0150.pdf |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Rodrigues|first= Ana Mar\u00eda S.A.|title= Reassessing the roles of women as 'makers' of medieval art and architecture|chapter = The Treasures and Foundations of Isabel, Beatriz, Elisenda and Leonor: The Art Patronage of Four Iberian Queens in the Fourteenth Century|editor= Martin, Therese|publisher= Brill |location = Leiden|volume= II| year= 2012|isbn= 9789004228320|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Beatrice of Castile, Queen of Portugal (1359)}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Queen consort of Portugal]]|before=[[Elizabeth of Aragon]]|after=[[Leonor Teles]]|years=7 January 1325{{snd}}28 May 1357}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Portuguese consorts}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Castile, Beatrice of}}\n[[Category:1293 births]]\n[[Category:1359 deaths]]\n[[Category:Castilian House of Ivrea|Beatrice]]\n[[Category:Castilian infantas]]\n[[Category:Portuguese queens consort]]\n[[Category:13th-century Portuguese people]]\n[[Category:13th-century Portuguese women]]\n[[Category:14th-century Portuguese women]]\n[[Category:14th-century Portuguese people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{other people|Beatrice of Castile}}\n{{Infobox royalty|consort=yes\n| name         = Beatrice of Castile\n| image = Beatrice of Castile (1293-1359).jpg\n| caption =\n| succession   = [[Queen consort of Portugal]]\n| reign        = 7 January 1325{{snd}}28 May 1357\n| spouse       = [[Afonso IV, King of Portugal]]\n| issue        =  [[Maria of Portugal, Queen of Castile|Maria, Queen of Castile]]<br>[[Peter I of Portugal]]<br> [[Eleanor of Portugal, Queen of Aragon|Eleanor, Queen of Aragon]]\n| issue-pipe   = Among others\u2026\n| issue-link   = #Issue\n| house        = [[Castilian House of Ivrea]]\n| father       = [[Sancho IV, King of Castile]]\n| mother       = [[Mar\u00eda de Molina]]\n| birth_date   = 8 March 1293\n| birth_place  =\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1359|10|25|1293|||df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Lisbon]], Portugal\n| burial_place = [[Lisbon Cathedral]]\n}}\n'''Beatrice of Castile''' or '''Beatriz''' (8 March 1293{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=350}}{{snd}}25 October 1359),{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=314}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} was an [[infanta]] of [[Crown of Castile|Castile]], daughter of [[Sancho IV of Castile|Sancho IV]] and [[Mar\u00eda de Molina]]. She was [[List of Portuguese consorts|Queen of Portugal]] from the accession of her husband, [[Afonso IV]],{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=305}} until his death on 28 May 1357.{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=311}}\n\n== Biography ==\n=== Family origins and early years ===\nDaughter of Sancho IV  and of Mar\u00eda de Molina,{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=312}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=215}} Infanta Beatrice was born in [[Toro, Zamora|Toro]]. She had six siblings, including King [[Ferdinand IV of Castile]] and  Queen [[Isabella of Castile, Queen of Aragon|Isabella]], wife of King  [[James II of Aragon]], and later duchess as the wife of [[John III, Duke of Brittany]].{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=215}}\n\nOn 13 September 1297, when Beatrice was only four years old, the bilateral agreement, known as the [[Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices]], was signed between Castile and Portugal, putting an end to the hostilities between both kingdoms and establishing the definitive borders. The treaty was signed by Queen Mar\u00eda de Molina, as the [[regent]] of Castile on behalf of her son, Ferdinand IV, who was still a minor, and King Denis of Portugal. To reinforce the peace, the agreement included clauses arranging the marriages of King Ferdinand and [[Constance of Portugal]] and that of her brother, Afonso, with Beatrice; that is, the marriage of two siblings, infantes of Portugal, with two other siblings, infantes of Castile.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=215}}{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|pp=350-351}}{{Sfn|Gonz\u00e1lez M\u00ednguez|2004|p=228\u2013229}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|The marriage of Ferdinand and Constance had been negotiated in a previous agreement signed on 15 September 1291. King Sancho IV of Castile  later negotiated the marriage of his son Ferdinand with Blanche, daughter of King [[Philip IV of France]].{{Sfn|Gonz\u00e1lez M\u00ednguez|2004|pp=225\u2013226}} The [[Engagement|betrothal]] of Ferdinand and Constance was ratified as part of the Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices in 1297.{{Sfn|Gonz\u00e1lez M\u00ednguez|2004|p=228}}}}\n\nBeatrice abandoned Castile in the same year and moved to the neighboring kingdom where she was raised in the court of King Denis together with her future spouse, Infante Afonso, who at that time was about six years old.{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=354}} Her future father-in-law \"had inherited from his grandfather, [[Alfonso X of Castile]], a love of letters, literature, Portuguese poetry, and the art of the [[troubadour]]s\" and Beatrice grew up in this refined environment.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=215-216}} Two of the Portuguese king's illegitimate sons, both important figures in the kingdom's cultural panorama, were also at the court: [[Pedro Afonso, Count of Barcelos]], a poet and troubadour and the author of ''Cr\u00f3nica Geral de Espanha'' and the ''Livro de Linhagens''; and, [[Afonso Sanches, Lord of Albuquerque|Afonso Sanches]], the favorite son of King Denis and a celebrated troubadour.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=216}}\n\n=== ''Arras'' and properties===\n[[File:Obidos 05.JPG|thumb|300px|[[\u00d3bidos, Portugal|\u00d3bidos castle]], given to Beatrice by her son Peter I of Portugal]]\nAfter the signing of the Treaty of Alca\u00f1ices and upon their return to Portugal, King Denis gave his future daughter-in-law the ''[[Las arras|Carta de Arras]]'' (wedding tokens) which included the ''[[Manorialism|se\u00f1or\u00edos]]'' of [[\u00c9vora]], [[Vila Vi\u00e7osa]], [[Vila Real, Portugal|Vila Real]] and [[Vila Nova de Gaia]] which generated an annual income of more than 6000 pounds of the old Portuguese currency.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=216}}{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=354}} After the marriage, these estates were increased. In 1321, her husband, who had not ascended to the throne yet, gave her [[Viana do Alentejo]]; in 1325, he gave her other properties in [[Santar\u00e9m, Portugal|Santar\u00e9m]]; in 1337, properties in Atalaia; in 1341, a manor house in [[Alenquer, Portugal|Alenquer]]; in 1350, the prior  of the Monastery of San Vicente de Fora gave her Melide, a manor house in [[Sintra]]; and later, in 1357, her son, King Peter, gave her more estates which included [[\u00d3bidos, Portugal|\u00d3bidos]], [[Atouguia, Our\u00e9m|Atouguia]], [[Torres Novas]], [[Our\u00e9m]], [[Porto de M\u00f3s]], and Chilheiros.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=227}}\n\n=== Marriage ===\nThe marriage was celebrated in Lisbon on 12 September 1309.{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=312}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} Before the marriage could take place, a [[papal dispensation]] was required since Afonso was a great-grandson of King Alfonso X of Castile through his illegitimate daughter, [[Beatrice of Castile (1242\u20131303)|Beatrice of Castile]], and Beatrice, betrothed to Afonso, was a granddaughter of the same Castilian king. In 1301, [[Pope Boniface VIII]] issued the [[papal bull]] authorizing the marriage, but since both were underage, it was postponed until 1309 when Afonso was eighteen years old and Beatrice had turned sixteen.{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=355}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=216-217}} It was a fertile and apparently happy marriage. Afonso broke the tradition of previous kings and did not have any children out of wedlock.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|\"We assume that after the marriage of dona Beatriz and don Alfonso IV, married life was harmonious (...) based on the fact that D. Afonso IV did not have any bastard children, thereby breaking a long family tradition\" (loose translation){{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=356}}}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|\"Perhaps since he had so many problems with those of his father, D. Afonso did not have any illegitimate children.\" (loose translation){{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|\"There are no known bastard children of the king. Two possible explanations could be the ties of profound esteem, friendship and respect that existed because he had been raised and had lived from a very early age with his future wife or, perhaps, because he wanted to avoid that his heirs had the same problems that he had had with his bastard brothers\".(loose translation){{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}}} Four out of the seven children born of this marriage died in their infancy.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=216-217}}\n\n=== A reconciling queen ===\nLike her mother-in-law, [[Elizabeth of Aragon]], who had raised her as a child, during her marriage Beatrice played a relevant role in the affairs of the kingdom and was \"the first foreign-born queen who was perfectly versed in the language and customs of Portugal which facilitated her role as a mediator of conflicts\".{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=225}} She discreetly supported her husband when he confronted his father on account of his half-brother, Afonso Sanches. In 1325 after the death of King Denis, Afonso \"who had not forgotten former hatreds\", demanded to be acclaimed king by the [[Curia regis|court]] and was responsible for having his half brother [[Jo\u00e3o Afonso, Lord of Lous\u00e3|Jo\u00e3o Afonso]] killed, and his great rival, his other bastard brother, Afonso Sanches, banished to Castile\".{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=222}}\n\nWhen her husband and her son-in-law King Alfonso XI of Castile fought in the war that took place in 1336{{snd}}1339, Beatrice crossed the border and went to [[Badajoz]] to meet the Castilian king to try to reach an agreement that would bring peace to both kingdoms, although her efforts proved to be fruitless.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=223}} She sent her ambassadors in 1338 to the court of King [[Alfonso IV of Aragon]] to strengthen the alliance between both kingdoms which had been weakened when her son, the future King Peter I of Portugal, refused to marry Blanche, a niece of the Aragonese king because of her proven \"mental weakness (...) and her incapacity for marriage\".{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=223}}\n\nQueen Beatrice and Guilherme de la Garde, [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Braga#List of Archishops of Braga|Archbishop of Braga]], acted as mediators in the quarrel, which lasted almost one year and posed the threat of another civil war in the Kingdom of Portugal following the assassination of [[In\u00e9s de Castro]],{{Sfn|Louren\u00e7o Menino|2008|p=355}} and in 1355, father and son reached an agreement.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=223}}\n\nOn the religious front, she founded a hospital in 1329 in Lisbon and later, with her husband, the Hospital da S\u00e9 to treat twenty-four poor people of both sexes, providing the institution with all that was required for its day-to-day maintenance.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=226}} In her [[Will and testament|last wills]] and [[Codicil (will)|codicil]], she left many properties and sums for religious establishments, particularly for the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] and [[Franciscan]] orders, and asked to be buried wearing the simple robe of the latter order.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=236-237}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=314}}\n\n=== Issue ===\nBeatrice and Alfonso IV were the parents of the following infantes:\n\n* [[Maria of Portugal, Queen of Castile|Maria]] (1313{{snd}}18 January 1357),{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|pp=315, 317 and 322}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} was the wife of [[Alfonso XI of Castile]],{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} and mother of the future king [[Peter I of Castile]]. Due to the affair of her husband with his mistress [[Leonor de Guzm\u00e1n]] \"it was an unfortunate union from the start, contributing to dampening the relations of both kingdoms\";{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=218}} \n* Afonso ([[Penela]], 1315{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}{{snd}}1317), heir to the throne, died in his infancy.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} Buried at the disappeared Convento das Donas of the Dominican Order in Santar\u00e9m;{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}  \n* Denis (born 12 February 1317 in Santar\u00e9m),{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}} heir to the throne, died a few months after his birth,{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|He died sometime before 13 June 1317 as evidenced by a letter from [[Pope John XII]] to King Denis expressing his condolences for the death of his grandson.{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201, n.208}}}} and was buried in [[Alcoba\u00e7a Monastery]];{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}} \n* [[Peter I of Portugal|Peter]] (8 April 1320{{snd}}18 January 1367), the first surviving male offspring, he succeeded his father.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} {{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} When his wife [[Constance of Pe\u00f1afiel|Constance]] died in 1345, Queen Beatrice took care of the education of the two orphans, the infantes [[Maria, Marchioness of Tortosa|Maria]] and Ferdinand, who later reigned as King [[Ferdinand I of Portugal]];{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=228-229}}\n* Isabel (21 December 1324{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{snd}}11 July 1326{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}), buried at the [[Monastery of Santa Clara-a-Velha]] in [[Coimbra]];{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}  \n* John (23 September 1326{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}{{snd}}21 June 1327{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}), buried at the [[Monastery of S\u00e3o Dinis de Odivelas]];{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}\n* [[Eleanor of Portugal, Queen of Aragon|Eleanor]] (1328{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=359}}{{snd}}1348), born in the same year as her sister Maria's wedding,{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} she married King [[Peter IV of Aragon]] in November 1347 in Barcelona{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=362}} and died a year after her marriage succumbing to the Black Death.{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=363}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=217, 220}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}\n\n=== Death and burial===\n[[File:Cloisters of S\u00e9 de Lisboa - Jun 2009.jpg|thumb|Cloisters of Lisbon Cathedral where King Ferdinand IV and Beatrice of Castile were buried]]\nQueen Beatrice executed three wills and one codicil.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=232-233}} She died in Lisbon when she was 66 years old and was buried at [[Lisbon Cathedral]] next to her husband as she had stipulated in her will.{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=314}} While the definitive tombs were being built, the royal couple was originally buried at the choir of the church and it was not until the reign of King [[John I of Portugal|John I]] that their remains were transferred to the new sepulchers in the main chapel of the cathedral.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=234-235}} These sepulchers were destroyed during the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake]] and were replaced in the 18th century. The ''Livros do Cart\u00f3iro da S\u00e9'' (Charters of the Cathedral) written between 1710 and 1716, describe the burial of Queen Beatrice, very similar to that of her husband, with an engraving that read: ''Beatriz Portugaliae Regina / Affonsi Quarti Uxor''.(Beatrice Queen of Portugal, wife of Afonso IV).{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=238}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite news|last= Gonz\u00e1lez M\u00ednguez|first = C\u00e9sar|year = 2004|title = Fernando IV de Castilla (1295-1312): Perfil de un reinado|work = Espacio, Tiempo y Forma, Serie III, Historia Medieval|number= 17| pages=223\u2013244|publisher = Universidad Nacional de Educaci\u00f3n a Distancia (UNED), Facultad de Geograf\u00eda e Historia |location = Madrid| issn = 0214-9745| url  = http://e-spacio.uned.es/fez/eserv/bibliuned:ETFB795938A-A8EF-AC9F-1889-B989699FFC79/Documento.pdf|language=ES|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite news|last = Louren\u00e7o Menino|first = Vanda Lisa|year = 2008|title = Cartas de Arras da Rainha D. Beatriz (1309-1359)|work = Estudios human\u00edsticos. Historia|number = 7|pages = 349\u2013358|publisher = Universidad de Le\u00f3n: Servicio de Publicaciones|location = Le\u00f3n|language = PT|issn = 1696-0300|url = http://buleria.unileon.es/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10612/1167/EUH-7-12.pdf?sequence=1|ref = harv|access-date = 11 June 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140418233835/http://buleria.unileon.es/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10612/1167/EUH-7-12.pdf?sequence=1|archive-date = 18 April 2014|url-status = dead}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Rodrigues Oliveira|first= Ana|title= Rainhas medievais de Portugal. Dezassete mulheres, duas dinastias, quatro s\u00e9culos de Hist\u00f3ria|language= PT |publisher= A esfera dos livros |location = Lisbon| year= 2010|isbn= 978-989-626-261-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last = Sotto Mayor Pizarro|first = Jos\u00e9 Augusto|title = Linhagens Medievais Portuguesas: Genealogias e Estrat\u00e9gias (1279-1325|location =Oporto|publisher=Doctorate thesis, author\u2019s edition|year= 1997|language = PT |url=http://hdl.handle.net/10216/18023|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last =Sousa|first =Ant\u00f3nio Caetano de|title = Historia